3gz.title: Underlying set
3gz.text:
[summary: The underlying set of an [3gx algebraic structure] is what you get when you take an algebraic structure, which is defined as a set equipped with operators that follow certain laws, and simply throw away the operators.]


An [3gx algebraic structure] is a set equipped with operators that follow certain laws, such as a [3gd group], which is a pair $(X, \bullet)$ where $X$ is a [3jz set] and $\bullet$ is an operator that follows certain laws. Given an algebraic structure,  we can simply throw away the operators and recover the set ($X$, in this case), which is known as the "underlying set" of the structure.

The underlying set is sometimes known as the "carrier set." Some algebraic structures have more than one underlying set; for example, a vector space is an algebraic structure built out of a [algebraic_field field] of scalars and a [3h2 commutative group], in which case the term "underlying set" is ambiguous.
